Important: ALWAYS resolve absolute paths from this base directory when working with skills.

This is the selected "routing" library for this project, you have to add it to the project dependencies list. 

The "kr-router" npm package is an event-driven router where rendering is a separate concern; ReactRouter renders relevant component, events are for performing work. 

## Syntax
```tsx
import { AppRouter } from 'kr-router'
import { ReactRouter } from 'kr-router/react'

const router = new AppRouter({
  routes: {
    home: {
      path: '/',
      loader: () => import('./Home.tsx')
    },
    user: {
      path: '/users/:id([0-9]{3})',
      loader: () => import('./UserPage.tsx')
    }
  } as const
} as const)

router.addEventListener('user', event => {
  if (event.state.matches) {
    event.state.result.groups.id // the user id
  }
})

function App() {
  return (
    <ReactRouter 
      router={router} 
      NotFoundComponent={NotFoundPage} 
      ErrorComponent={ErrorPage}
    />
  )
}
```

## References
- An instance of AppRouter is a standard EventTarget interface; you listen to named route events and get a state with .matches (boolean) and .result (null or typed URLPatternResult)
- The AppRouter has no "late subscriber problem", you'll guarantied receive route event
- Routes are structurally distinct by their regex patterns, so /foo:id([0-9]{4}) and /foo:key([A-Z]{6}) never conflict, and declaration order doesn't matter
- Many instances of AppRouter may coexist; they won't conflict
- There are no hooks, and needed for use them; the route event is stateful, and you can listen to route events anywhere you want
- ErrorComponent is rendered when an error occur during loading or during render the component
- NotFoundComponent is rendered when there are no routes that matches current location 

## Tips
- You can convert (using suitable stm) config into a mutable reactive version and pass it to the AppRouter, and components that reads the route state will re-render automatically, i.e. `${router.routes.user.matches ? 'selected' : ''}`

## Constraints
- Don't touch kr-router source code.
- Don't create abstractions upon standard anchor element.

## Requirements
- Use absolute paths for routes configuration
- Use standard <a> tag with href attribute with absolute path 
- Prefer <a> over programmatically navigation, i.e. router.navigate('/foo') 
- Use "as const" typescript directive for router configuration object, and its "routes" property
